sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36458
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This actuator, upon receiving a Polymerase per Second (PoPS) signal, creates 3 proteins that induce cell lysis in E. Coli. Each protein is paired with a Ribosome Binding Site already included in the sequence. This part has been proven to have consistent success in cell lysis of E. Coli. The three proteins transcribed from the sequence are a Holin (lysis the cell by inserting itself in the plasma membrane and causing cell lysis after reaching a critical mass), an Endolysin (destabilizes the cell wall), and an Rz Protein (helps the holin enter the plasma membrane). The sequence is void of all repeats and palindromes greater than or equal to 10 bp thus allowing it to be synthesized with relative ease. To use this product one would simply have to pair this part with a sensor that would then send a PoPS signal and cause the cell to lyse. This actuator has been proven to cause lysis even at very low levels of activation. Despite this, it has also been shown to not cause lysis unless activated.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Max Whitmeyer
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequences for all three proteins were found from Part BBa_K124017 in the BioBricks registry. All Ribosome Binding Sites and the Terminator found from the biofab website in the data section.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The sequence was altered in a few places in order to avoid repeats and palindromes. Also, the sequence had to be edited further when the Ribosome Binding Sites(RBS) were added to avoid repeats. It's also important to note that the part utilizes one Bicistronic Design(BCD) and two Monocistronic Designs(MCD) for the RBS's. Three BCDs would have been used but all BCDs have significant overlapping sequences and only one could be used to avoid repeats. All RBS's were chosen for low to medium expression level and low variance.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36451
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the sequence used to synthesize holin proteins which are used for cell lysis. Holins insert themselves in the plasma membrane of a cell and lyse the cell upon reaching a critical mass.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Max Whitmeyer, Ian Lewis
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part came from Part BBa_K124017 in the BioBricks registry - a cell lysis package. This is the first sequence from the package.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Repeats and palindromes greater than length 10 had to be altered in order to synthesize the DNA.
